{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536950"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:12:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:12:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15845"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15845"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.28,0.22,0.43,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8536"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63529"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8536"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15845"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48983"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"476"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"7883"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20482"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63529"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman re-presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of sore throat, fever, and fatigue. She was prescribed amoxicillin two days ago by another doctor for presumed bacterial pharyngitis. Today she has developed a widespread, non-itchy rash. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.  She has not had amoxicillin previously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears tired but well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. She has bilateral tender cervical lymphadenopathy and tonsillar enlargement with exudates. There is a widespread blanching maculopapular rash across her trunk and limbs. Her spleen is palpable 2 cm below the costal margin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue amoxicillin and add antihistamine","Switch to erythromycin and document penicillin allergy","Cease amoxicillin and document penicillin allergy","Cease amoxicillin without documenting allergy","Continue amoxicillin and add prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of infectious mononucleosis caused by Epstein-Barr virus (EBV): fever, pharyngitis, lymphadenopathy, splenomegaly, and fatigue. Bloods may show mild liver dysfunction and leukocytosis.  It is common in children and young adults.The development of a maculopapular morbilliform rash after starting beta-lactam antbiotics is a well-documented phenomenon in EBV infection, occurring after 1 - 3 days in up to 90% of patients who receive aminopenicillins.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease amoxicillin without documenting allergy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. The rash is not a true allergic reaction but rather a result of a temporary interaction between the virus and the antibiotic. Future use of penicillins is not contraindicated and the patient should be firmly counselled on this. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease amoxicillin and document penicillin allergy\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this reaction is not a true allergy. Documenting it as such could unnecessarily restrict future antibiotic options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue amoxicillin and add prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E would be incorrect as antibiotics are not indicated for viral pharyngitis, and steroids are only indicated in severe cases with marked tonsillar swelling causing airway compromise which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitch to erythromycin and document penicillin allergy\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this is a viral infection that does not require antibiotics. The original prescription of amoxicillin was likely based on the misdiagnosis of bacterial pharyngitis, and as mentioned above, this is not an allergy but arash secondary to the interaction with the virus itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue amoxicillin and add antihistamine\u003C/strong\u003E would be incorrect as the rash is not histamine-mediated and antibiotics should be ceased as they are not indicated for viral infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement should focus on supportive care including adequate hydration, rest, and analgesia. The patient should also be advised to avoid contact sports for at least four weeks due to the risk of splenic rupture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ampicillin or amoxicillin administration in acute Epstein-Barr virus infection commonly causes a maculopapular rash.","The rash associated with EBV and aminopenicillins is not a true drug allergy and does not contraindicate future penicillin use."],"references":["\u00d3nodi-Nagy K, Kiny\u00f3 \u00c1, Meszes A, Garaczi E, Kem\u00e9ny L, Bata-Cs\u00f6rg\u0151 Z. Amoxicillin rash in patients with infectious mononucleosis: evidence of true drug sensitization. Allergy Asthma Clinical Immunology. 2015.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4362637/","Zhang R, Mao Z, Xu C, Wang W, Kwong JS, Xu M, Song Y, Lv T, Teng Z, Zhong R, Liu H, Liu Y, Wang Q, Wang Y, Zhang Y, Chen S, Chai X, He R, Zheng W, Zhang J. 2023. Association between Antibiotic Exposure and the Risk of Rash in Children with Infectious Mononucleosis: a Multicenter, Retrospective Cohort Study. Antimicrobial Chemotherapy. 2023.  Available at: https://journals.asm.org/doi/10.1128/aac.00249-23"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15845"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48983"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:58:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T14:00:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8536"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63529"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"positio